events.name: Developer and Tech Holiday Party
events.description:
Please RSVP on the Eventbrite page.

The holidays are upon us again and provides us a great excuse to get together as community.  The Omaha Mobile Meetup, NebraskaJS, Beer and Code Omaha, Omaha Java Users Group, Open Nebraska, Omaha .Net User's Group have joined forces to throw a Developer & Tech Holiday Party on Wednesday December 2nd, from 5pm to 9pm at the Beercade in Benson. This event is open to all of the great Developers and Technologist around our community.  Come on out and share knowldge, stories, and drinks with the entire community.  Meet new people, catch up with all freinds, and see how great our tech community can be working together.

Thanks to our generous sponsors, we'll have snacks and an open tab for happy hour, available on a first come, first serve basis. Once our funds run out, you'll be on your own for drinks. If you'd like to attend, please RSVP so we have an estimate of how many people will be coming, but please join us even if you don't get a chance to RSVP. 

We're still actively seeking sponsors for this community event. If you or your company is interested in sponsoring, please contact Kevin Berry ( kberry (at) AdviseDesign.com ) or any of the organizers of the supporting groups.  Developer & Tech Happy Hour events are grassroots initiatives organized by tech leaders in Omaha to support our need to make connections within the tech community. We would greatly appreciate your support, and we will openly recognize your efforts in supporting this initiative. In return for your support, you'll get your logo on the event site, you can hand out great swag at our event, and we'll make announcements during the event to thank you and our other great sponsors so that the tech community knows who loves and supports them.

events.name: Android Development for Beginners - Study Jam - Part 1
events.description:
You do not need to have any previous development experience.  This will be great for people interested in learning programming and people interested in learning Android.  All ages welcome. We are planning on 2 parts with the next part April 2nd at the same time.  You must attend part 1 to attend part 2 and ensure you have availability to attend both before you RSVP.  Best part is we are making this all free. This will be partially sponsored by Google so we should have swag.  We plan on having lunch and drinks provided as well.  $1,000+ in prizes.  We will limit the number of people who can take this class so RSVP ASAP!

Here's how it works:
1) RSVP to this event
2) Sign up using the below link. It will take you to the free beginner material. If you want to get started early you can go to "Access Course Material" after you signup below:
https://www.udacity.com/account/affiliate/GoogleStudyJams
3) Join this group to talk to others taking this class around the world - https://plus.google.com/u/0/communities/107779414017676143474
4) You should bring a laptop with Android Studio installed before coming to the meeting.  Please comment if you have any issues.
5) By the end of the class you will be able to create an Android app and call yourself an Android developer!  Also if you submit the final project you will get a certificate from Google!

Join this group to chat to others who are taking this class and the mentors:
https://gdgomahainvite.herokuapp.com/

One of our personal goals is to get more local Android developers.  So come out to our meetups to keep learning.

If you have any questions please comment on this event.

events.name: Android Development for Beginners - Study Jam - Part 2
events.description:
This is part 2 of the class.  We will pick up where we left off.  The expectation is you have an emulator or device setup and have run hello world on it before you come to class.  For anyone that joins this class that was not in the class before please ensure you have run hello world on a device or emulator and we will pick up on practice 1 after you run hello world.  Also setup these two things before class:

Udacity - j.mp/devstudyjams

Slack - bit.ly/GDGOmahaSlack

events.name: Workshop Night
events.description:
Next Monday we will be hosting a workshop night downtown at Agape Red. For the people who attended the Study Jam, this will be an opportunity for you to continue/finish your udacity course. There will be a few mentors there to help you with any questions you might have. If you are unable to make it to this workshop night, we will have a live hangout session during this time period so you can ask questions remotely from your home.

This event is open to everyone. If you didn't attend the Study Jam you are more than welcome to come and work on things with other android developers! 

Requirements for the Final Project:

Should teach a user 5 things about a topic

Can contain text, images, and other Views

Should be limited to a single screen that can scroll

Can link to other apps like maps, phone dialer, web browser, etc…

Should be interactive with buttons

Things you should not do:
An app with multiple screens

Storing user’s preferences/data on the device

Getting data from a server

Syncing data across devices

events.name: Google I/O Extended - Free One Day Conference
events.description:
Are you not able to attend Google I/O this year but still want in on the keynote, meet with other cool developers, and like-minded techies? This is a 100% free event!

Google's annual developer-focused conference, kicks off May 18th. Around $1,000 of swag and prizes(Ex: VR Google Cardboards)

Schedule:
9-9:15 Mingle/Register
9:15-10:05 Polymer Code Lab - Abraham Serafino
9:15-10:05 Progressive Web Apps with Angular 2 - Jake Partusch
10:10-11 Firebase Code Lab - TBD
10:10-11 Material Design Talk - Victor Cassone
11-12 Lunch(Jimmy Johns)
11:30-11:55 Do Space Intro to 3D printing lab
12-2 Keynote
2-3 Break/VR Party?!?
3-4 What's New in Android
4-5 Android Pay Everywhere
4-5 Image Compression

*Subject to change
*Talks between 9-11 will not be streamed and will be presented from Metro Community College @ Do Space

FAQs

Will all sessions be streamed or just the keynote?

We are streaming the keynote and other talks and codelabs planned for attendees. Any sessions that are streamed will also be available to watch later on the Google Developers YouTube channel.

How can I get my work to let me attend?

We suggest to treat this like any other conference and ask your employer if they would allow you to attend the free conference and hopefully they will pay for you to go. There will be many other cool developers to network with and you will learn from the keynote, talks, and codelabs.

Sponsors:
Metro Community College @ Do Space - Location
Object Partners - Food
Google - Swag/Prizes
Agape Red - Snacks/Drinks

We are looking forward to seeing you there!

We are following the NEJS code of conduct
http://nebraskajs.com/conduct/

events.name: Diving head first into Kotlin: No more excuses - Brandon Gogetap
events.description:
If you didn't tune into Google I/O this year, one of the biggest and most exciting announcements regarding Android was Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android. Full interoperability with Java, closures, mix-ins, and extension functions are just some of the features of Kotlin and now you can utilize them in your Android app.

First, we will have a roundtable discussion about what Google announced this year. We will discuss whatever the group wants and please join the conversation! AI, machine learning, Actions on Google, and of course Android! We may not have the answers, but we will have a good chat. 

Brandon will give a quick intro into the language and then jump into live coding examples to show how using Kotlin in your project can improve productivity, make your codebase more robust, and make Android development more fun.

Join us to learn about Android and to meet other Android Developers. 

Agenda:

6:00pm Architecture Components
David Corrado

LiveData is an observable data holder class. Unlike a regular observable, LiveData is lifecycle-aware, meaning it respects the lifecycle of other app components, such as activities, fragments, or services. This awareness ensures LiveData only updates app component observers that are in an active lifecycle state.

6:30pm An Introduction to Template Apps
Parshav Chauhan

In this talk we will go over build types, build variants and product flavors in your app's build configuration. Configuration of gradle builds in an app can be useful during app development and management. We then take a look into how these configurations can be useful in creating template apps.

Kotlin is now an official language on Android. It's expressive, concise, and powerful. Best of all, it's interoperable with our existing Android languages and runtime.

See Kotlin & Android's home page to learn more: https://developer.android.com/kotlin/

6:30pm React Native
Jordan Petersen

React Native lets you build mobile apps using only JavaScript. It uses the same design as React, letting you compose a rich mobile UI from declarative components.

See React Native's GitHub page to learn more: https://facebook.github.io/react-native/

events.name: All-Day Workshop: Learn to Build Voice Actions with the Google Assistant
events.description:
Build Actions for Your Community with the Google Assistant!

Come out and learn together how to build a conversational voice interface for the Google Assistant on Google Home, Android, Wear OS, Android Auto, etc.

This event is completely FREE and open to all! You don't need to have any programming experience to participate (but even experienced developers should come ready to learn a lot)!

We will have big group instructional presentations in the morning and small group hands-on time in the afternoon. The goal is to build an "action" or skill for any community you're involved in (like a professional network, interest group, or your hometown) using the Google Assistant platform.

All you need to bring is a laptop.

CRi will be providing breakfast pizza, coffee, and juice!

Buildertrend will be providing Varsity's pizza & salad for lunch as well as a happy hour at the end of the day!

GDG Omaha will provide snacks, swag, and raffle prizes!

For more information about building Actions for the Google Assistant, see here: https://developers.google.com/actions/

events.name: Flutter Study Jam
events.description:
Flutter is Google’s mobile app SDK for crafting high-quality native interfaces on iOS and Android in record time. Flutter works with existing code, is used by developers and organizations around the world, and is free and open source.

Want to get started on building Flutter apps?

Join us for our Flutter Study Jam! Together we'll work through the Flutter Udacity Course prepared by Google instructors. You will be able to get hands-on experience with Flutter and build a Flutter app while learning the fundamentals.

What to bring:
- A laptop! The course will run on all of the latest versions of popular browsers. For the best experience, your laptop should have Flutter installed on it prior to starting the study jam to save time. Check out: https://flutter.io/get-started/install/
- Headphones/Earbuds if you want to work through the material at your own pace.

Also, check out our Slack community here: http://bit.ly/GDGOmahaSlack
There is a #flutter channel that we can use before, during, and after the workshop.

Agenda:
9:00am: Welcome & Set-up
9:15am: Flutter Udacity Course Introduction
9:30am: Udacity Course Lesson 1: The Flutter Framework
11:30am: Lunch (will be provided by OPI!)
1:00pm: Udacity Course Lesson 2: Building Interactive Apps
4:00pm: Wrap-up & Raffle
5:00pm: Event ends
